So my position is that they should probably return to Athens because they make most sense and mean most in context and it’s the right thing for the art and the objects. But that’s the argument. Not one of natural rights.
And it’s a VERY difficult and confusing argument with lots of implications to say that they “naturally” belong in Greece that could very easily be reappropriated to almost all cultural artifacts.

Because while ownership is complex, they weren’t stolen, and had they stayed in Ottoman controlled Athens (where the Acropolis was used to store ammunition and occasionally had catastrophic fires) they would have been destroyed.

Effectively, I think it’s a very big and complicated and dangerous argument to say that the Elgin marbles must belong to Greece because they were created there, or to say they should be returned because they were stolen.

My honest position is that yes, the UK should return the Elgin marbles to be *located* in Athens, but that the questions of ownership, provenance and precedent are really important and very complicated and should be investigated very carefully.

3/3 At its core, semantics exists because of its amazing ability to add contextual meaning around data so it can be better understood, searched, and shared, enabling both people and computers to see and discover relationships in the data. - Semantic for Dummies, Allen Taylor

2/3 Semantics goes further by providing a universal framework (RDF) to describe and link data, not just documents. Today, semantics is still often discussed in the context of the “semantic web,” but it’s more appropriately viewed as a new way of modeling data.

1/3 Originally, semantics was envisioned as an evolution of the web. It provides a standard format for linking data that isn’t too different from the once revolutionary idea of using HTML and HTTP standards to share and link documents on the web.
